The variable we are trying to predict is represented by the variable, RainTomorrow in the data set. The domain of the column RainTomorrow is {Yes, No}. ‘Yes’ indicates that it will rain tomorrow and ‘No’ indicates that it will not rain tomorrow. With my particular data set, the proportion of rainy days to fine days is 26.45%. This indicates that there are significantly more fine days in comparison to rainy days, thus, the data set is quite inbalanced.

From analysing the numeric predictor variables, we observe that there are a lot of missing values in the data set. For example, the variable Sunshine only has 357 complete observations. This is a problem as it will have an effect on the accuracy of certain models that lack the ability to handle missing values well. In fact, certain models like Random Forest do not accept missing values at all. In order to evaluate the different models fairly and for the sake of consistency, I will only include complete cases and omit all rows with any missing values.

Furthermore, some variables like humidity and the speed of the strongest wind gust have quite high standard deviations. This may have an impact on certain models like the Decision Tree where a small change in the input may lead to drastic changes in the results. However, in this case, this is not a reason to exclude these variables completely from the initial testing of the models. We can see that some of these observations, like Rainfall, Evaporation, Sunshine etc. also contain a large number of values that are 0. I will still include these rows in my analysis because I cannot assume that these values were recorded as 0 because there were no observations for this variable made that day. For example, especially for Rainfall, a value of 0 might represent the fact that there was no rain at all that day. Finally, the level of skew remains low for most variables (except for rainfall). For these reasons as well as the fact that I have no prior information about the context of these variables, I am not justified in removing any of them completely from my analysis. Thus, I will include all variables to build my model. Note that I will include Day, Month, Year and Location as certain times and certain locations might have an effect on the likeliness of it raining tomorrow.

To construct ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) curves, the confidence intervals for each model are calculated. Then, the ROC curves are plotted according to these confidence levels with the True Positive Rate on the y-axis and the False Positive Rate on the x-axis. True Positive Rate is a measure of the ability of the model to correctly predict Yes when it should predict Yes while the False Positive Rate are referred to as false alarms. Thus, the goal for a classifier is to have a low false positive rate and a high true positive rate. However, from the plot above, we can observe that having a high true positive rate will also result in a lot of false alarms which is not desirable. Thus, plotting the ROC curves of each model will help us find a confidence level where there is a healthy balance between the True Positive Rate and the False Positive Rate. ROC curves are also helpful to compare classifiers because given that there is a certain level of confidence we aspire to achieve, ROC curves will help you find the classifier that is more suitable to these conditions and produce the best results. Furthermore, the AUC values, which is the area under the ROC curve, can be calculated to give us a tangible, numerical value to accurately compare the classifiers. A higher AUC value is more desirable than a low one. A further analysis into the comparison between classifiers will be included in part 6.

Random Forest wins as the best classifier if accuracy, AUC values, precision and recall are prioritised in this order. However, note that Random Forest, Naive Bayes, Boosting and Bagging are quite comparible in their performance. Their measurements are quite favourable with accuracy remaining above 84% and AUC values being above 70% for these models. Random Forest is the most precise which means that it is able to pick out true positives very well out of those that are predicted as positives. Naive Bayes has the highest recall, meaning it is able to pick out true positives very well out of those observations that are actually positive. While precision is quite high for most of the tree based algorithms (Random Forest, Naive Bayes, Boosting and Bagging), these models have extremely low recall. This might be due to the overfitting of the trees which can cause the model to not generalise well. Decision Tree, on the other hand, performs signficiantly worse than all other classifiers with almost a 10% decrease in accuracy and a 9% decrease in AUC value in comparison to the next worse classifier (Bagging). Its precision and recall values are both significantly low as well.

Usually, decision tree algorithms employs top-down, greedy search and aims to create homogenous leaf nodes. At each stage, we attempt to find the attribute that allows for the highest information gain and split the tree according to this attribute until finally arriving at a leaf node where the data will be classified. From the plot of the decision tree as shown in part 4, we can observe that the variable Sunshine is at the root which means that this attribute led to the highest information gain in the beginning. We will dive deeper into variable importance in part 7. As previously mentioned, the decision tree model performed the worst, achieving an accuracy of 74.39% after predicting 52 No’s correctly and 8 Yes’s correcly out of a total of 82 observations. Precision and recall are both less than 50%, which are quite low. In the plot of ROC curves, the line for the decision tree remains well below the other classifiers and this is reflected with the low AUC value as well. The weak performance of the Decision Tree model can be due to a variety of factors such as overfitting (when the model does not generalise well) or underfitting (when the model is too simple), or not enough data, or high statistical variance, etc. Furthermore, it is expected that the Decision Tree will perform worse than ensemble methods like Random Forest, Boosting and Bagging as those models make use of multiple classifiers (often decision trees) and combine the results of each classifier. This allows for the creation of a better classifier from a collection of weaker classifier.

In the case of Bagging, it will make multiple replicates of the original data with sampling, with replacement, from the training set and construct a single classifier for each replicate. The classifiers are combined by taking a majority vote to produce the final decision. With our sample and with default settings, Bagging achieves an accuracy of 84.15% after predicting 62 No’s and 7 Yes’s correctly. It has a high precision of 83% but very low recall of 29.41% which again, suggests that the model is overfitting. In the default settings, the number of trees for Bagging is set to 100 but perhaps to improve recall, this parameter could be adjusted accordingly. In terms of ROC curve and AUC values, the model performs reasonably well although not as good as Random Forest, Naive Bayes and Boosting. In fact, to achieve a high true positive rate, there is a certain interval where Bagging performs slightly worse than the random classifier. Thus, Bagging might not be the best model to use for our sample.

Boosting is another ensemble method. With this method, multiple trees are grown slowly and training examples are weighted, with a higher weight given to examples that are difficult to classify. The final classification is made after performing a weighted sum of each classifier where classifiers that are more accurate are given a greater weight. As mentioned before, our data set is quite imbalanced in terms of rainy days to fine days. Bosting supposedly improves the classification of imbalanced data sets. In comparison to Bagging, we see this proven as Boosting increases accuracy by 2% to 86.159 after predicting 64 No’s and 7 Yes’s correctly. Precision is high at 87.5% but recall is extremely low at 41.18%. This is to be expected as boosting is known to be prone to overfitting which yields low recall. In terms of ROC curves and AUC values, Boosting performs extremely well in comparison to the other classifiers, though not as well as Naive Bayes. Overall, Boosting is quite a good model to use for our sample.

The idea of a Naive Bayes classification is to maximize the posterior probability (probability of belonging to a class given that a certain set of attributes are true). For a Naive Bayes Model, independence between attributes is assumed. The performance of the Naive Bayes model is very similar to boosting, achieving the same accuracy of 86.59% after predicting 60 No’s and 11 Yes’s correctly out of a total of 82 observations. Precision is lower than other tree-based ensemble classifiers at 69% but Naive Bayes achieves the highest recall of 64.71%. Furthermore, Naive Bayes has the highest AUC value at 84.5%. This is significantly higher (approximately a 7% increase) than the next best AUC value. One reason for the relatively good performance of Naive Bayes might be because it is quite robust to isolated noise points. This suggests that it handles outliers quite well. Thus, since our data contains a few variables with high standard deviations and a high level of skew, this might be a reason as to why Naive Bayes was able to achieve quite a high accuracy. Naive Bayes is also robust to irrelevant attributes. Since I included all the original attributes, this might be another reason why Naive Bayes was able to achieve the level of accuracy as it did as it was able to distinguish between those that are important and those that are not. Nevertheless, we “naively” assumed independence for this model and there are a variety of techniques that we could employ to improve upon it. For example, if the independence assumption does not actually hold, which, for our data set, it certainly does not has variables like Evaporation probably affect other variables like Humidity, we can employ another model called Bayesesian Belief Networks.

Finally, Random Forest is another ensemble method that improves upon the bagged decision trees model. It creates multiple data sets from the training set and uses subsets of data points and subsets of attributes. A decision tree classifier is built for each data set and like bagging, the final decision is made by taking a majority vote after combining the classifiers. As previously mentioned, Random Forest achieves the best accuracy, 87.08%, out of all the other methods. It predicted 65 No’s and 7 Yes’s correctly out of the total 82 observations in our test set. It achieves 100% precision meaning that out of all the cases that were predicted to be positive, all were correctly identified as positive (that it will actually rain tomorrow). Recall is very low at 41.18%, however, we have seen that this is the case for all other tree-based classifiers and suggests that the model is overfitting the data. In terms of ROC curves and AUC values, although not the best, Random Forest performs reasonably well at 76.88%. As mentioned before, it is not a surprise that Random Forest performed signficantly better than the individual decision tree. Nevertheless, there are some disadvantages like the fact that it is less interpretable than an individual decision tree and that it uses a lot of memory to compute. However, since our data set is quite small, this is not a huge issue.

For Naive Bayes, it is impossible to analyse the variables that are important in constructing the model which is why it is not included in the data frame above. This is one weakness for Naive Bayes. For the Decision Tree, no rank is assigned to the variables indicating the importance, thus, in the data frame above, the important variables that are used in the construction of the tree are labelled as 1 and those that are not used are labelled as 0. Some of the variables included in the tree construction are Sunshine, Humidity, Wind Direction, and more. The rest of the models use a certain metric to show the importance of an attribute, with higher values corresponding to more relevant attributes and lower values corresponding to less important attributes. Different models may rank the importance of the same variable differently. For example, Sunshine is the most important variable for Bagging and Random Forest but the wind direction at 3pm is the important varaible for Boosting. For all models, we can safely eliminate variables that are 0 or close to 0 in terms of the importance values above. For example, for decision tree, we can safely delete RainToday, Location, Rainfall, WindSpeed3pm, and all others that are labelled as 0 in the data frame above. This is because these variables are not used in the tree construction at all. For the rest of the models, it seems like we can only eliminate RainToday safely and perhaps Location as well. Analysing variable importance can be an important tool for feature selection when attempting to build a better classifier. This technique will be explored in part 8.

Part 8: Creating an Improved Tree-Based Classifier

# Use Random Forest

# Reset data frame
WAUS = read.csv("WAUS2020.csv")
L = as.data.frame(c(1:49))
set.seed(30990971)  # Setting my StudentID as the random seed.
L = L[sample(nrow(L), 10, replace=FALSE),]    # Sample 10 locations.
WAUS = WAUS[(WAUS$Location %in% L),]
WAUS = WAUS[sample(nrow(WAUS), 2000, replace=FALSE),]   # Sample 2000 rows.
rownames(WAUS) = NULL

# order important variables in random forest model
rf.importance = rf.importance[order(rf.importance$`Random Forest`, decreasing=TRUE),]

# create data frame to see how many features create the best accuracy
df = NULL
df = data.frame(NumFeatures=c(0), Accuracy=c(0), AUC=c(0), Precision=c(0), Recall = c(0), row.names=NULL)

# start loop
for (i in 1:nrow(rf.importance)) {
  # feature selection
  important.vars = as.vector(rf.importance[1:i,1])
  important.vars = c(important.vars, "RainTomorrow")
  WAUSoriginal = WAUS
  WAUS = select(WAUS, important.vars)
  WAUS = na.omit(WAUS)
  
  # create training and test sets
  set.seed(9999)
  train.row = sample(1:nrow(WAUS), 0.8*nrow(WAUS))
  WAUS.train = WAUS[train.row,]
  WAUS.test = WAUS[-train.row,]
  
  # cross validation
  tControl = trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
  mtry=c(1:length(WAUS))
  rfGrid = expand.grid(.mtry=mtry)
  ntree = 500
  
  set.seed(30990971)
  WAUS.rf = train(RainTomorrow~., data=WAUS.train, method='rf', metric="Accuracy", tuneGrid = rfGrid, trControl=tControl, ntree=ntree)
  
  # testing the model
  WAUSrf.pred = predict(WAUS.rf, WAUS.test)
  WAUSrf.matrix = table(actual=WAUS.test$RainTomorrow, predicted=WAUSrf.pred)
  
  # accuracy
  rf.accuracy = sum(diag(WAUSrf.matrix)) / sum(WAUSrf.matrix)
  
  # precision (TP / TP + FP)
  rf.precision = WAUSrf.matrix[2,2] / sum(WAUSrf.matrix[,2])
  
  # recall (TP / TP + FN)
  rf.recall = WAUSrf.matrix[2,2] / sum(WAUSrf.matrix[2,])
  
  # confidence level- do predictions as probabilities and draw ROC
  WAUSrf.ppred = predict(WAUS.rf, WAUS.test, type="prob")
  # head(WAUSrf.ppred)
  
  # computing ROC curve and plotting on top of decision tree
  WAUSrfpred = ROCR::prediction(as.numeric(WAUSrf.ppred[,2]), as.numeric(WAUS.test$RainTomorrow))
  WAUSrfperf = ROCR::performance(WAUSrfpred, "tpr", "fpr")
  
  rf.cauc = performance(WAUSrfpred, "auc")
  rf.auc = as.numeric(rf.cauc@y.values)
  
  df = rbind(df, c(i, rf.accuracy, rf.auc, rf.precision, rf.recall))
  WAUS = WAUSoriginal
}

df = df[-1,]
rownames(df) = NULL

# plot measures against the number of features
g = ggplot(data=df, aes(x=NumFeatures)) + geom_line(aes(y=Accuracy, colour="Accuracy"))
g = g + geom_line(aes(y=AUC, colour="AUC"))
g = g + geom_line(aes(y=Precision, colour="Precision"))
g = g + geom_line(aes(y=Recall, colour="Recall"))
g = g + scale_colour_manual("Measures", breaks = c("Accuracy", "AUC", "Precision", "Recall"), values=c("blue", "pink", "blueviolet", "orange"))
g = g + ggtitle("Changes in Measures as the Number of Features Increases")
g = g + ylab("Measure (Proportion)")
g = g + xlab("Number of Features")
g = g + scale_x_discrete(limits=c(1:24))

print(df)
print(g)

In this part, I explored how to create an improved tree-based classifier through cross validation, parameter tuning and feature selection. Since Random Forest was already a strong tree-based model overall as we have discovered in part 6, I decided to build upon this.

Using the caret package, I performed a 10-fold cross validation repeated 5 times. This is when the algorithm partitions the data into 10 disjoint sets, trains on 9 partitions and tests on the remaining one. This process is repeated 5 times. Cross validation can help improve upon the original classifier as it lets you fit the model over a variety of different training and testing sets rather than just one.

For parameter tuning, I experimented with modifying the mtry parameter in tuneGrid and changing the number of trees. For the tuneGrid parameter in the train function, I set the number of randomly selected predictors (mtry) to be the number of variables used in the model. After having tried many different tree sizes, I found that setting the paramter to 500 trees yielded the best accuracy. This might be because using more trees might have led to overfitting and on the opposite spectrum, using less trees might have led to underfitting.

As for feature selection, I used the analysis we performed for variable importance in part 7. The original Random Forest model was able to rank the variable in order of importance with a metric called the Mean Decrease Gini. A high Mean Decrease Gini measurement corresponded to the variable being of higher importance in the model. To find a good selection of features to include in this improved model, I attempted to fit the model n different times, where n is the total number of variables in the original data set. At each attempt, I included one additional feature and the features were included in order of descending Mean Decrease Gini scores (signalling variable importance) as found in part 7. Thus, the first iteration included the most important variable, the second iteration included the two most important variables, and so on.

From the plot above, we can see how accuracy, AUC, precision and recall changes as we include more and more attributes. There seems to be no direct trend but we can see that a selection of the 12 most important features yields the best results. Referring to the data frame, we see that by including the 12 most important features in our model, we are able to achieve an accuracy of 95%, 100% precision, 66.67% recall and an AUC value of 89.43%. These measurements are significantly better than all the models we have created- approximately 7% increase in accuracy and 4% AUC than the best model measurements in the previous part (and about 12% increase in AUC from the original Random Forest model).

Thus, we have shown that after parameter tuning and cross validation, we are able to create a much improved Random Forest classifier. Note that I also attempted to perform cross validation and parameter tuning with the Boosting and Bagging methods. This is shown in the appendix below. Bagging was able to increase its accuracy by about 0.5% and AUC by 1% while boosting increased its accuracy by about 2% and AUC by 3%. While the accuracy and AUC generally improved for both models, the results were not as great as what this improved random forest model achieved. Furthermore, I was not able to experiment with feature selection with these improved bagging and boosting models as it required too much processing power.

Part 9: Implementing Artificial Neural Network

WAUS = read.csv("WAUS2020.csv")
L = as.data.frame(c(1:49))
set.seed(30990971)  # Setting my StudentID as the random seed.
L = L[sample(nrow(L), 10, replace=FALSE),]    # Sample 10 locations.
WAUS = WAUS[(WAUS$Location %in% L),]
WAUS = WAUS[sample(nrow(WAUS), 2000, replace=FALSE),]   # Sample 2000 rows.

# remove NA values
WAUS = na.omit(WAUS)
rownames(WAUS) = NULL

# recode output class as numeric
WAUS = WAUS %>% mutate(RainTomorrow=dplyr::recode(RainTomorrow, "Yes"=1, "No"=0))

WAUSmm = model.matrix(~WindGustDir+WindDir9am+WindDir3pm+RainToday, data=WAUS)
WAUS = cbind(WAUS, WAUSmm)
WAUS$WindGustDir = NULL
WAUS$WindDir9am = NULL
WAUS$WindDir3pm = NULL
WAUS$RainToday = NULL
WAUS$`(Intercept)` = NULL

# scaled normalization
col.num = which(colnames(WAUS)=="RainTomorrow")
scaledWAUS = scale(WAUS[,-c(col.num:length(WAUS))])
scaledWAUS = cbind(scaledWAUS, as.data.frame(WAUS[,c(col.num:length(WAUS))]))

# create training and test sets
set.seed(30990971)
train.row = sample(1:nrow(scaledWAUS), 0.8*nrow(scaledWAUS))
WAUS.train = scaledWAUS[train.row,]
WAUS.test = scaledWAUS[-train.row,]

# fit model
n = names(WAUS.train)
f = as.formula(paste("RainTomorrow ~", paste(n[!n %in% "RainTomorrow"], collapse=" + ")))

set.seed(30990971)
WAUS.nn = neuralnet(f, data=WAUS.train, hidden=1, linear.output=FALSE)

# predict
col.num = which(colnames(WAUS.test)=="RainTomorrow")
WAUS.pred = neuralnet::compute(WAUS.nn, WAUS.test[,-col.num])
results = data.frame(actual=WAUS.test$RainTomorrow, prediction = WAUS.pred$net.result)

# round predictions to 0 or 1
WAUS.predr = sapply(results, round, digits=0)
WAUS.predrdf = data.frame(WAUS.predr)
attach(WAUS.predrdf)
WAUSmatrix = table(actual, prediction)
detach(WAUS.predrdf)

accuracy = sum(diag(WAUSmatrix)) / sum(WAUSmatrix)
# precision (TP / TP + FP)
precision = WAUSmatrix[2, 2] / sum(WAUSmatrix[,2])
# recall (TP / TP + FN)
recall = WAUS[2,2] / sum(WAUSmatrix[2,])

plot(WAUS.nn, cex=0.5, rep="best")

cat('\nConfusion matrix\n')
print(WAUSmatrix)
cat('\nAccuracy: ')
print(accuracy)
cat('\nPrecision: ')
print(precision)
cat('\nRecall: ')
print(recall)

In this part, we explored the use of an artificial neural network to predict whether or not it will rain tomorrow. Pre-processing data is a requirement before implementing an artifical neural network. As with our previous models, all missing values are omitted from the data set. Artificial neural networks requires the data to be numerical, thus, indicator columns were created for each categorical attribute. In order to do this, I used ‘recode’ to convert the output class (RainTomorrow). Yes’s were converted into 1 and No’s were converted into 0. For the other categorical attributes, I used ‘model.matrix’ to convert them into numerical data. Another requirement of artificial neural networks is for the data to be normalised to a common scale. This is achived through the inbuilt ‘scale’ function which scales values by using the mean and standard deviation of the data set. Normalization is important as failure to do so might result in the prediction value remaining the same regardless of input values. Furthermore, I included all the attributes in this model because the previous analysis on variable importance was based on specific classifiers, thus, it is not justified to carry those conclusions to this model. Variables that are not important in those models might be important in this model and vice versa. Finally, I set the hidden layer to 1 because after having tried with up to 20 hidden layers, I observed no difference in the results.

With artificial neural networks, we are able to achieve an accuracy of 81.8% after having predicted 38 No’s and 7 Yes’s correctly. Precision is comparable to Naive Bayes at 64% but this model achieved the highest recall of 69.23% which is even higher than the improved Random Forest model. This might be because artificial neural networks are not as prone to overfitting as tree-based classifiers are. This model is significantly better than the individual Decision Tree model but quite comparable to Bagging, Boosting, Naive Bayes and Random Forest. In fact, it is not able to achieve an accuracy as high as the ensemble methods. This might be because our data set is fairly small and artificial neural networks would work a lot better with a larger data set. Perhaps we also need to further tune the number of hidden layers through trial and error to achieve a higher accuracy or we could also experiment with normalising the data in a different way.

Conclusion

To summarise, we observed that a basic decision tree yielded the worst accuracy for attempting to predict whether or not it will rain tomorrow in certain locations in Australia based on a set of variables. The most accurate model in terms of accuracy was Random Forest followed by Naive Bayes, Boosting, and then Bagging, in that order. Considering AUC values, Naive Bayes was the best, followed by Boosting, Random Forest, Bagging and then Decision Tree. From examining variable importance, we realise that different models come to different conclusions as to which attributes are the most important, however, we notice that across all models, there seems to be a consensus that RainToday can be eliminated with very little effect on performance. After building upon the random forest model with cross validation, parameter tuning and feature selection, we were able to achieve a significantly higher accuracy of 95% and an AUC value of 89% in comparison to the previous models implemented with default settings. Finally, after implementing an Artificial Neural Network classifier, we concluded that it while it is significantly better than the decision tree model, it is comparable to the other ensemble methods.

WAUS.rf = train(RainTomorrow~., data=WAUS.train, method='AdaBoost.M1', metric="Accuracy", tuneGrid = rfGrid, trControl=tControl)

# testing the model
WAUSrf.pred = predict(WAUS.rf, WAUS.test)
WAUSrf.matrix = table(actual=WAUS.test$RainTomorrow, predicted=WAUSrf.pred)

# accuracy
rf.accuracy = sum(diag(WAUSrf.matrix)) / sum(WAUSrf.matrix)

# precision (TP / TP + FP)
rf.precision = WAUSrf.matrix[2,2] / sum(WAUSrf.matrix[,2])

# recall (TP / TP + FN)
rf.recall = WAUSrf.matrix[2,2] / sum(WAUSrf.matrix[2,])

# confidence level- do predictions as probabilities and draw ROC
WAUSrf.ppred = predict(WAUS.rf, WAUS.test, type="prob")
# head(WAUSrf.ppred)

# computing ROC curve and plotting on top of decision tree
WAUSrfpred = ROCR::prediction(as.numeric(WAUSrf.ppred[,2]), as.numeric(WAUS.test$RainTomorrow))
WAUSrfperf = ROCR::performance(WAUSrfpred, "tpr", "fpr")

rf.cauc = performance(WAUSrfpred, "auc")
rf.auc = as.numeric(rf.cauc@y.values)

cat('Confusion Matrix\n')
print(WAUSrf.matrix)
cat('\nAccuracy: ')
print(rf.accuracy)
cat('\nPrecision: ')
print(rf.precision)
cat('\nRecall: ')
print(rf.recall)
cat('\nAUC: ')
print(rf.auc)
